  "text": "Learning about context is a critical contributor to sex differences in context fear conditioning, where males are reported as showing stronger context fear conditioning [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and more activation of hippocampus [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] during acquisition and consolidation of context fear conditioning compared with females. Given the role of dorsal hippocampus in context representations [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , and the requirement of context representation for context fear conditioning [CITATION_10] , these findings suggest that males have stronger encoding of context representations and thus more precise context fear memory.",
